a: Retired from serious competition 2021, no longer completely sound.
OTTB, over hurdles in Ireland. Bites at slightest provocation, AKA 'Sharkface'. Cause of death: collapsed after winning Weston 2022, suspected heart attack.
Legendary eventing sire. First ever stallion to win Badminton. Cause of death: sudden collapse in paddock.
Crowdfunded to the tune of Â£500,000 by fans for Jonty Evans, who promptly fell off him (2018, six weeks in a coma).
'She kicks and she bites and she pins her ears'. AKA The Troll, AKA Piranhica. Trainer jokes that she kills babies; a baby doll is now kept in her stall and sometimes ends up in the water bucket.
Started by Piggy, then moved around a bit til Paul Tapner retired and offered Piggy the ride back. Doesn't give her best at one-days. A bit fragile, ties-up and has soft feet.
Was at one time so difficult to mount that he had to be mounted in the lorry and ridden down the ramp.
7/8 blood, out of the Monart sales. Another of those 'rider says he's 17hh' geldings.
Of unknown warmblood/Thoroughbred breeding. 'Galloping machine', thinks dressage is a waste of time.
Previous name Loroto He's a Star.
Owned by Katie Preston from a two-year-old.
After a character in Gossip Girl.
By a Thoroughbred out of a Clydesdale, allegedly. Biggest feet in eventing, the V8 Supercob.
Very strong. Ridden in a heavy bit - in 2015 once broke his bit on the gallops and bolted.
Already had his stable name when Emily Philp bought him in Ireland. The family named him over dinner.
An Andrew Nicholson ride towards the end of Nicholson's 5* career. Oliver says he's beautifully produced.
Was bought as a hunter and Pony Club horse, but got too strong so the owner approached Julia Norman to event him when he was 9.
Sire is a Thoroughbred, dam is 1/4 Shire.
Oliver says he's 17hh but his registration disagrees.
Ros's World Champion and king of the yard. Loves big events, a good boy who wouldn't hurt a fly. By a Selle Francis showjumper, the Galoubet A line.
Broke the dressage record at Badminton in 2019 with a 19.7.
A little bit of a barn favourite. Oliver Townend gives him the best stable, which can be seen from the house.

Bought in France, ridden initially by Sammi Birch. 'Unbelievably sharp', hard to catch, can't be jumped at home because he bolts and has to be loaded last because he gets excited. Loves competing, showing off, and crowds.
By Jumbo out of a Thoroughbred. When bought, considered 'hairy and big-boned'.
Can be aggressive in his stable, so wears an Equilume mask with blue LEDs, a technique invented to alter perceived day length in broodmares.
Frightened of crowds, 'bit of a nutcase'.
Lives mostly outside. Has a Shetland pony friend called Sooty who keeps him calm.
'Miley' for his miles of leg as a foal.
His owner bred her hunter mare to an advanced eventing stallion. Dumped his rider at Badminton 2016 and jumped three fences upstream towards the stables.
Gentle giant, 'horse of a lifetime' for Alex Bragg.
Breeding is Dutch warmblood x Thoroughbred.
Previous name Bannerfarm Rocket. Started by Padraig McCarthy, then briefly by Andrew Nicholson.
A big horse, described as lanky at 12.
Was Kirsty Short's Pony Club horse, she owned him from a four year old. Used to be a runaway but goes mostly in a snaffle now.
Owned by Alicia Hawker's grandfather, who used to breed racehorses. Likes to escape his field and graze with the dairy cows.
Bought by Tom Jackson's parents at four. Described at that time as gangly, cheap, and cribbing. Makes trouble by removing his own headcollar and rugs.
Bought from a hunting yard at 4, 'nothing special .. moved like a sewing machine'. Has heavy feather in the off season.
Cause of death: destroyed suspensory ligament at Badminton 2018.
Bought by Warren Lamperd as an unbroken broodmare. Described as 'Free range' because if they try to keep her in one paddock, she jumps between them. Likes sunbathing and scratches under the jaw.
Homebred grandson of Louise Harwood's Pony Club mare. Nephew to Bit of a Barney and Partly Pickled.
Racing name Smart Gorky. Known as the Deer. Injury-prone in turnout and has to be hand-grazed. Hates hacking, bolts home.
Named after a near miss when he ate a poisonous plant as a foal. Raised on a farm but frightened of tractors.
Intended ride of the deceased George Crawford, headed to Badminton 2019 under Emily Parker in his memory but sadly withdrawn. A big horse, 'makes Harelaw Wizard look small'.
Out of a Thoroughbred. William Fox-Pitt won Pau on his sire, the Selle Francais Oslo Biats. Owned by the Oratorio II syndicate. Started by Laura Collett but he was too big for her.
Named for his close-set eyes. Bought by Caroline Clarke as a newly broke 4-year-old, when she was 16.
It's pronounced 'Dunlock'.
Racing name Kalinga Demo. Has an 'over-excited, almost neurotic' dual personality that Elisa Wallace calls 'The Dragon'.
Described by Tina Cook as a racing reject.
Full brother to Nereo.
Dozey, laid-back yard favourite.
Cause of death: broken pastern at Pau 2017.
Previous name Quattro Van De Kwakkelhoek. AKA the Mighty Duck.
Cause of death: broken fetlock at Belton 2016.
Michael Owen credits this horse with getting him through the death of his teenage sister in a car crash.
Froggy because he's French, Vendredi because he was foaled on a Friday. Rolls, bucks, bites his stablemates.
Cause of death: complications after injury at Burghley 2017.
Racing name Big Jet. Raced hard, sometimes consecutive days, on bad tracks in the outback. Scouted by Boyd Martin after his race retirement.
Racing name Captain Frank. Said to have a similar attitude to Jack Sparrow, being grumpy and scrappy.
Remarkably flaxen tail.
Racing name My Gifted Indyanna. Unraced because her farm was sold up by owner Alex Trebek. Nearly died after foaling Laguna Seca.
'Nuts, out of control and generally we hated riding him'. Very strong and gets worse if you put a heavy bit on him.
Nervous in big arenas, which affects his dressage.
Named after basketball player Kobe Bryant.
Breeding is Thoroughbred x Irish Draught.
Sire a TB, damsire a Clydesdale. According to Ben Hobday's hashtags, 'used to pull carts' and '5 star cob'.
When his showjumping wasn't much good, was broken to drive. 'Like a pet, wanders around the yard without a headcollar.'
Born on the 4th of July.
Bought as a foal, Rachel Robinson turned down Andrew Nicholson when he offered to buy him from her. Has one-sided facial paralysis after a freak accident in his lorry as a two-year-old.
According to Sarah Bullimore, 'evil' at 5 but merely 'sharp' at 9.
Failed showjumper. 'Spooky as hell' on hacks, David Britnell will only take him out with a neck strap.
Has struggled with stamina cross-country, but now has a new fitness regime.
Bad at being caught. Jumps fences to get away unless you tempt him with a bucket of food.
Hallie Coon bought her having only seen a video.
The horse that got Tricia Pytches back into eventing in her mid-50s. 'Green as a cabbage' when she bought him at five.
Everyone's favourite little golden pony. Has his own Facebook page. Unknown heritage but probably has Connemara - has no idea he's 15.1.
Was Jonelle's ride til 2017 pregnancy, Tim got to keep her afterwards.
By a Connemara out of a Thoroughbred. When first bought, was such a naughty pony they used to call him 'Rat'.
Small, unimpressive, 'permanent hay belly'.
Was dyed pink in late 2015 by Emma Hyslop-Webb for a breast cancer charity.
Broke his pelvis as a young horse, before Emily bought him at 4. 'Not an oil painting, but a really good jumper.'
Bought from Portugal. Timid at first, has built confidence. Nosy and has a central stall at the barn so he can see what's going on. Likes carrots and sweet potatoes.
Remarkably white, even for a grey.
Name is a portmanteau of his sire and damsire, Caresino and Levernois.
Out of a TB by a Welsh cob.
A bit spooky. Sara Gumbiner blames his Irish heritage,and once felt the need to check whether she could fall off XC on the flat, and still continue.
Racing name Shykee's Thunder.
Racing name Heir Pegasus. Bought by Kevin McNab for $300, very lame and badly behaved. His sire has a reputation for 'difficult' horses.
Trained to race but never actually went.
Breeding is Holsteiner/TB.
'Tiny but with a massive stride'. Snaffle-mouthed and uses a rubber bit in dressage.
Racing name Chivas Royale.
Racing name Tsu Tsu Ro.
Adorable long ears. Has a non-competing horse friend called PJ, who he refuses to be without at home. A happy, calm hacker.
Sweetest little pony face. Breeding is Connemara/TB.
Unraced, racing name Constock.
Trakehner/TB breeding. Barn diva.
Named after basketball player Reggie Miller. Sometimes coughs due to throat surgery, so isn't bridled until the last minute before dressage. His groom rode him down the aisle at her wedding.
Cause of death: cancer.
By the TRAK stallion Fleetwater Opposition out of a Thoroughbred. 'The ugliest foal you've ever seen' with an enormous head and mismatched front feet. Cause of death: seizure.
Bred by Tim Price's parents.
Cause of death: unknown, during retirement.
A crowd favourite, though he be but little, he is fierce.
Cause of death: euthanised, unknown cause.
Cause of death: neurological issue.
Homebred out of Louise Harwood's Pony Club mare. Full brother to Bit of a Barney and uncle to Mr Potts.
Cause of death: injury in Young Rider class at Weston.
Same mother as Opposition Buzz.
Named after Manuel from Fawlty Towers. AKA 'Spinhead', spins in circles when excited. Once sent home from a hunt for being disruptive.
Cause of death: unknown, during retirement.
Homebred out of Louise Harwood's Pony Club mare. Full brother to Partly Pickled and uncle to Mr Potts.
Bought off the track for $850. Survived a barn fire in 2011, three months before Burghley. Boyd Martin calls him the Legend.
Race name was War Buckaroo.
Cause of death: acute encephalitis.
Cause of death: complications after colic surgery.

Named Oscar because he's a grouch at home.
Cause of death: heart attack.
Ex-racer. Thinks he's people. Downhill and not much of a front end when starting out, Emily Beshear calls him 'spaghetti legs'.
Breeding is Thoroughbred x Oldenburg.

Ex-racer, born in Kentucky.
Cause of death: presumed aneurysm.

Brought Jessica Phoenix up through the levels.
Cause of death: presumed aneurysm.

Ex-racer from New Zealand.
Cause of death: aortic aneurysm.
Ex-racer from Maryland.

Throws a few happy crow-hops after a good showjumping round.
Cause of death: unknown, during retirement.
Son of Jaguar Mail. Owned by the Salty syndicate.
The 'HANN' is a bit optimistic, sometimes marked 'unknown breeding'. Bought unbroken in Scotland, and brought up by Ellen Cameron.
Lots of flax, lots of chrome, and a belly spot. With his pretty orange and white colours, known as The Koi.
By Master Imp.
Over-jumps, refuses to touch a rail or even a brush fence. Keen on his food, wears a grazing muzzle.

Never raced because he threw his jockeys, then when tried as a lesson horse, threw everyone else. Jumps for fun, repeatedly jumped out of his field. Now so good-natured Buck Davidson let spectators pat him during a hold on course.
Won $67,250 on the track.
Lives in Frankie Thieriot Stutes's back garden and lets her kids sit on him. Likes a croissant and a nap after competing. When first bought, 'really ugly with the personality of Eeyore'.
Excitable and can be strong cross-country. Owned by George Hilton-Jones's mother Isabelle.
Retired from top level 2022. 'We will miss his big-white-path-finding-nose on cross-country day terribly.'
Won Burghley Young Horse at 5.
Sired by Calvaro. Bought by Kirsty Chabert as a 5 year old.
5* debut in 2021. Was briefly an Emily Philp ride. Padraig says she's sweet and easy to do.
Joseph: 'A handsome gentleman with a laid back attitude.' Owned by the Way Forward syndicate.
Badminton debut 2022. Nice gallop, tricky in the first phase. David: 'The nimble lady of the yard â an elegant picture with a really swanky walk.'
Nicola's European champion. JL prefix stands for his owners' names as BE already registered a Dublin. Can get overexcited and noisy in the warmup.
Owned by the Eael Grey Tea Partygoers syndicate.
Owned by Aistis since he was 5.
'Loves everyone and everything', especially cuddles. Registered black, but 'dark bay' on Francis's website - I think maybe he just sun-fades.
Tamie's 'horse of a lifetime'. 'Wiggly' on the flat, Tamie reckons his flash looks help his scores.
Bought off a Facebook post from a showjumper, aged 5.
'Micheal' is the registered spelling - does get misreported. DOB is New Year's Day. Leg markings are estimated, please correct after dressage.
Bred at Kirsty Chabert's stud, by Opposition Heracles (son of Fleetwater Opposition). Owned by the Daisy Chain syndicate. First 5*, horse is so low-profile I can't find its leg markings recorded.
By an Olympic team jumping stallion. Padraig: 'big and white'.
Started and produced by Ros Canter, ridden by Tom McEwen while Ros was pregnant.

David was asked by the owner if he'd take this one to sell, and ended up keeping it (doesn't own). Wasn't impressed at first - straight hind legs and corrective shoes in front! Friendly if you take time to say hello.
Yes, it's spelled like that.
Joseph: 'a very sensitive type'.
